ce:section.ce:para:
The results of the uncertainty analysis (see Table 6) indicate that under conservative assumptions (using only radial thermal conductivity), the mean Bi for 18650 and 26650 cells are 0.032 and 0.045, respectively. This is below the threshold of 0.1 for the lumped capacitance assumption, and is on the scale of previously reported values [30]. When considering the upper 95th percentile, the Biot number at 25 °C marginally exceeds this threshold for the 18650 cells (
Bi = 0 . 110
), and more so for the larger diameter 26650 cells (
Bi = 0 . 156
). At elevated temperatures characteristic of thermal abuse (500 °C), the value rises to over 0.2 for each cell. Under the current knowledge of Li-ion cell thermal conductivity probability distributions, 18650 and 26650 cells will have negligible thermal gradients to a confidence level of 90% and 80%, respectively.
